  "description": [
    "a STOL XLI HO 22 WILMTNGTON N Cn SEPTEMBBB 25 1907 S1C0 PER YJMB v ULU ETO Reason for Retaining the TO DEWEY Resents Proposition that Islands Should be Abandoned The Strong Point of the Argument is Not Rased Upon the Military or Naval Importance of the Archipel ago but Upon Their Value Pres ent and Future in the Extension of Americas Trade With the Orient Washington Sept 21 Admiral Dewey strongly resents the proposi tion that has been discussed in a more or less academic manner to syrrender the Philippines which of all men he was a leading factor in bringing under the American flag In an interview today the admiral set out clearly the reasons which impel him to insist upon the retention of the islands Singularly enough in view of the fact that the admiral is a man of war by trade the strong point of his argument is not based uion the military or naval impor tance of the archipelago but almost altogether upon the great value pre sent and prospective of our trade with the Orient which he regards as holding out the best promise of com mercial expansion The admiral said Abandon the Phillippines"
